segments.text: talking about outhouses.
Yeah.
And you said that the university would replace them.
That's right, rebuild them and all that.
I don't know.
They may have taken them out there.
I just don't know.
But the bonfire, as you know it now, was originally held on the drill field.
But when they made the movie, we've never been licked.
They helped build that.
They bought the center pole.
They bought a whole bunch of poles and put on there, and we carried other stuff to make it up.
And a bonfire was held there, and Bill Stern, the NBC sports announcer, covered that bonfire because the Thanksgiving Day game was going to be, it wasn't on TV, I guess.
I guess it was on radio, but
because they didn't have TV.
Were you here when that movie was made?
Yes.
Describe any of your recollection of that, please.
Well, I was in two scenes in it.
Barton was marching into Savisa Hall, and the lead guy, I've forgotten his name, he was supposed to be in that outfit, and somebody was supposed to trip him.
We were supposed to walk over him.
and it was a stuntman, and we didn't step on the guy, you know, and they made us redo that until we'd step on him.
Then they had a scene in Sbisa, a dance, where there was supposed to be a fight, and we were in, I was in one of the crowd in there,
And the thing I remember most about that, of course, was we never really ever had a fight in the dance hall.
And we all had to take off our shoes so we wouldn't make noise because they were recording it.
And I don't know.
How long were those movie people around?
Do you remember?
They were here for a pretty good while.
Was it months or weeks?
Months.
There was more than a month.
And I presume that y'all were pretty excited about
Well, everybody, of course, wanted to meet the two gals.
And Gail, the cadet commander, was the escort of one of them at one of the ball games, and got on there.
Martha O'Driscoll, and she was a blonde.
I can't think of the other.
That brown-headed gal's name.
I know.
We were all
about seeing them out at Franklin's and what have you.
Did you get to see the movie soon after it was made?
Or were you gone by then?
I think we were gone.
I don't think I saw it until after I came back.
I was in the service because, no, that's another thing.
No, it was after I came back.
Now, you may have seen it.
I don't know.
You probably weren't on campus at this time, but where were you when you heard the news of D-Day?
You were at Fort Benning, Georgia.
Not D-Day, V-E-D. No, D-Day.
D-Day, I had just started OCS in Fort Benning, Georgia.
In fact, I've got the graduation program for that, and it started December 7, 1944.
June, not June 7.
June 7.
Right.
Not June 7.
Then another important memory.
Where were you when you heard the news that President Roosevelt had died?
Most of us.
Camp Shelby, Mississippi.
Camp Shelby is where we were when that happened.
We all wondered what was going to happen and how Harry was going to take over, you know.
Because you're a little older than I, but most of us didn't remember any president before Roosevelt, and we didn't know who the vice president was very much.
Let's see.
All right, you come back to the campus when?
After the war?
No, but when did you get back?
I came back, landed, I guess it was in, was it 45?
Did I start over here?
You came back in 46.
I guess it was 46.
I landed on Juneteenth in San Francisco, and we got on a troop train, and they started down here, and they took us to Fort Sam Houston.
I had called Dolores from San Francisco.
We spent one night in San Francisco and told her I was going to be in San Houston at San Antonio.
But I wasn't sure just what day.
I said, it's going to take us probably two days to get there on a train.
And the minute we came into Texas, the Texans began to bail off of that train.
But not a one of them missed.
When the train got to San Antonio, they were all there waiting for us.
Anyway, I got a hold of her and
And then I came back to A&M, I guess that September, didn't I?
Because I drove back and forth from Brenham for a while.
Couldn't find a place to live over here, so we drove back and forth, and that was before you could, you know, the road wasn't paved coming through the bottom.
That's when you came through Navasota and all.
About how long a drive did it, in time, did it take?
Well, we were out a little over an hour.
Now, if we could go through the bottom, it was a terrible road, and you could cut off a little bit of mileage, not much time.
What was your, you and your fellow veterans, how did your attitude about classwork change when you came back?
Of course, we were more serious about education.
Now, some of the guys that came back had not been commissioned, and they wanted to get back in the Corps.
And that was one of the few protests that I know that I participated in was when Gil Gilchrist was president.
I don't even remember what the Sam Hilley did.
But we didn't like it.
And we were going to get him fired.
We, the veterans.
And we met in the old assembly hall, and we got a couple of guys from the state legislature to come over.
And that assembly hall was packed, and people were on the outside.
I couldn't get in.
I was on the outside looking in.
And bless their heart,
the guys that were leading the veterans, those politicians turned them inside out.
I mean, not inside out, but they had them spun so anyway, that was the end of it, yeah.
Now, you were not in the Corps.
No, not then.
Because you had been commissioned.
Right.
And then, do you all finally locate a place to live over here?
Yeah.
Brian Field closed.
And
got housing by points, how long you've been in the service.
That's right.
And I finally, they finally had some quarters out there that we could move into.
They were tar paper shacks.
You heard them talk about the annex, but anyway, we had two rooms and a long hall.
I mean, two bedrooms, but the, except for us and the other apartments, the walls didn't go all the way to the ceiling or to the floor.
and a gas burner in there with an oven on it.

My dad got one of the men that worked for the company to bring out a few things over here in the truck, and we pulled up in front of that tar paper shack, and the man that was driving it and was helping us, he said, does your dad know that you're moving into this?
No.
But I breezed in there, and there was no kitchen, and there was no bathroom.
And I said, Perry, where is the bathroom?
And he said, well, it's just right down this sidewalk here, and it's called a lottery.
We were there two weeks, moved into College View.
Yeah.
All right, was College View filled with veterans?
Yes.
And it was, at that time, it was filled with veterans.
And they had gas burners, but they did have a sink that hung on the wall, and they had ice boxes.
And they had one bed that was kind of like a double bed, and then they had a cot.
Well, when we first moved in, we rented it, and then we began to get some, and I could get it.
And if you had it unrented... $24 a month.
$24 a month.
How adequate was the GI Bill to help pay your expenses?
Well, of course, I think they get $90 a month.
But they paid everything at A&M.
My books, drafting equipment, slide rules, anything we needed.
And I'm sure the profs had us buying books maybe that we didn't need.
I don't know.

we just signed a voucher and the government took care of that and they paid us $90 a month and and so what they paid for the rent and what little we could make I couldn't I worked some but they didn't work a whole lot because there just weren't too many there's so many people looking for jobs there weren't a lot around uh and Dolores was a very sharp shopper and uh

And they'd come, some of the older, other vets would be very enterprising, and they'd come through the place with a pool cart selling vegetables and eggs, you know, and a lot cheaper than you could buy.
We finally decided we'd make us a commissary in a garage, and it worked pretty good for a while.
So what it was was a...
A bulk buying association?
That's right, it was a mutual aid.
If I were to look at your transcript after the war grades compared to before the war grades, would I see any difference?
Yeah.
You were a better student after the war?
Yeah.
Were you and your veteran friends
aware that any of the faculty may have changed the way they did things with these veterans in class?
Because you were as old as some of the teachers, weren't you?
No, I never had a graduate assistant teaching.
I wasn't aware, and some of them may have been that got there, but
All of my teachers, professors, I never had a graduate student.
Al Chalk and all these others.
Of course, I've already mentioned a bunch of them that we had, but I just don't remember a graduate student.
Did you, as a veteran and his wife, did you all go to many student activities during those post-war years?
Well, when she was married, after we were married, they had a free movie at Grove, and they had dances at Grove.
We went to that several times.
Of course, you may remember I had a son and a baby on the way.
So you were busy pretty well all the time.
Did you go to Silver Taps after the war?
I was wondering if it may have had a different meaning.
We had silver taps, but the RVs were not involved in it.
And everybody shut down the lights and pulled the blinds.
And the outfit the guy lived in walked down and stood as a formation by Sully, and the buglers blew silver taps.
Let's see now, after the war, didn't Eisenhower make a famous visit here?
Yes.
Do you remember that?
Or was that, were you gone before he got here?
No.
I think I was still here because I remember him coming in the main gate, that's out on the east
on the East Gate, as you call, and he was escorted by the cavalry, the vehicle was, and they were carrying, they were mounted and they had lances.
They pretty soon did away with the cavalry, too.
But I think, I remember he made a, and he talked, I think Eisenhower was here twice, maybe just once.
Right, you graduate when?
I graduated in August of 1947.
Was there a commencement then?
No.
So did you ever go across the stage and officially?
I got two degrees from A&M, a bachelor and a master's, and I never ever participated in a ceremony here.
I participated in a military school graduation, but not here.
All right, let's see.
You didn't do a final review.
I did a final review.
When?
This was when they took the class of 44 and 45 in at the same time.
Describe it.
Well, the final review then was a lot different than it is now.
We farmed up just as they used to still do, except it was on the drill field.
And we marched around, and the seniors led us.
We came right back around and we reformed.
We didn't break and go to the dormitory and change clothes or anything else.
The only thing was you turned around and the fish got to drop their handle.
And then the seniors formed a line and moved across.
Then as now, the juniors, of course they were still wearing stripes and they took them around.
But they were all, almost all of them were
book privates in the Army, because that's what we were wearing then.
And they took them around, and then they came across in the class of 46 with their little stragglers made the last one.
I think it was, I don't remember whether it was raining or had rained, but it was, it was, that was very memorable and very emotional for all of us, because we knew we were leaving right after that.
When you graduate, what's your first employment after?
Teaching school in Brenham.
How well prepared did you feel A&M had made you for that first task?
I thought I was pretty well prepared.

Of course, I taught mechanical drawing and shop, and I had another one I called broadening and finding, and then I taught general math, which was for the, at that time, the high school had five grades.
They had eight, nine, 10, 11, and 12.
The ninth grade, if the kids weren't good enough to take algebra,
They had general math, and I taught general math.
He must have been equipped very, very well, because the students really thought he was good.
Yeah.
Right.
So now when do you come back to A&M as a staff member?
In March of 51.
And what was your task?
I'm sorry?
What did you do?
That's when I became a military counselor.
Right.
Describe that.
I'm sorry?
Describe that task.
Well, I can't remember the colonel's name that was here at that time.
It may have been Boatner.
That was Boatner.
Because they assigned me certain dorms to be, and since I was field artillery, I got a lot of the field artillery dormitories, also coast artillery dormitories.
And my duties were to discipline the kids in the corps, to inspect their rooms or see that they were cleaned and in proper shape.
And then I'd pull my regular duty every so often.
They'd be there at night until midnight, which I would make two rounds, one right after CQ and the other one just after taps.
And there were several comical incidents happened in that instance.
And two of them I remember very vividly, and she remembers one of them very vividly.
I was making my rounds, and I was over by dorm three, I guess it was.
And I looked over, and there was a guy standing outside a window in dorm two and just laughing.
And then pretty soon, he'd run inside.
And then he'd come back, and he'd just laugh.
And I got around over there, and I walked in.
Water up to my ankles.
And I said, where did all of this water come from?
What water, sir?
Well, then later on, on another incident, I walked by, and there's arm two to arm four, as I came by it out of the fourth floor.
and my mattress, another mattress, the beds, the desk, and the chairs, and by now I'm on my way up to the fourth floor.
Boy, I got up in a quick minute.
The bull hit the fan, everybody knows it.
Quiet as a church.
I said, I got the first sergeant, and I said, what's going on here?
He said, nothing, sir.
And I said, who threw out the, trashed out this room?
What room, sir?
And I walked right down and said, open this damn door.
And he opened it, and there were guys' clothes in there, and that was about it.
I had them go back downstairs and pull all that stuff in them, back up to the room.
While I'm doing that, one of the kids comes over and he says, Major Perry, your office is on fire.
My office was over in dorm five.
Well, I went over, my office wasn't on fire.
But somebody had gone in there, and the only thing I could think of is they, somehow they set black shoe polish on fire.
And this black smoke in the soot was all over that place.
You couldn't put your hand anywhere.
And I, oh boy, I was upset.
I had to call Dolores and I said, well, I'll tell you what, I'm gonna be late coming in because somebody has really fixed my room up.
I'm gonna find out who it is or my name is not Howard Perry.
Well, about three o'clock in the morning, I guess, somewhere like that, I walk in and I quietly open the back door, tell him what you said.
I said, hey, what's your name?
And he said, oh, hell, John Doe.
But when I got back to the office the next morning, it was all clean.
So I don't know who did it.
It may have been... Weldon Kruger was in school, and Perry had coached him in high school and taught him.
And I think Weldon cleaned all that up.
He may have had someone, because it took a lot to do it.
Weldon was a good Brenham boy.
Yeah.
I got him to come to A&M.
In fact, I was on a group that selected him as cadet colonel, but I didn't get to see him.
I was gone before he became cadet colonel.
Let's digress on that.
As far as you know, what has been the comparative lifetime success rate of the key student leaders at A&M, corps commanders and so forth?
Have they gone on to be successful?

Most of them that I know have gone on, and a lot of people that were not prominent in their schoolwork, I mean, without they weren't high achievers or didn't have a lot of rank, were very successful in their other lives.
And they all based it on their education at A&M, just like everybody does.
There's only one guy that, and this was after I left the Corps, when I came back again, but that's another story.
But it was a guy who was very prominent in the Corps, and he then became mayor of San Antonio, and got into trouble, and then fell on the cabinet.
I think he was a colonel when he was here, Boatner, later became newsworthy in Korea.
Describe him in personality and style.
Okay.
Colonel Boatner was, he was a true bull of the woods.
He always said exactly what was on his mind.
He moved from
Military science people all moved down to Foster and anyway, the one there by Leggett, across the street from Leggett, not on the same side of the street from Leggett, Ross Hall.
They tore Foster down.
Ross Hall was standing.
We called it the Pentagon, the small man's Pentagon.
ran the place with an iron hand, and they had two little couple of things on him.

They had two small cannons out in front, you know, and had a little grass they were trying to keep growing, and there was a freshman out there, and he was looking at one of these guns when Boatner walks up.
He says, cadet, what are you doing?
He said, I'm looking at this field artillery piece.
And he said, what do you think of it?
Oh, sir, I think the field artillery is the best branch of the service.
Boatner was infantry.
He said, well, get the hell off the grass.
We always knew when somebody was going to catch it because he always raised the windows in his office.
And what was the secretary's name?
Marie, no, that guy in green, oh, golly.
She was the secretary for the Commonwealth for a long time.
Fern Adams called her Ms. Newley.
Oh, you're talking about Jo.
We'd see her leaving.
Some of the others cleared out of that we knew.
That he was going to chew somebody out.
And he would use some very colorful language.

Well, somewhere before I graduated, I mean, left A&M, working there, the seniors decided they were going to rebel, and so they said they were going to turn in their buttons, and they were going to march to the Pentagon and
turn their buttons in.
Boatner met them on the street.
Halt!
What do you all want?
They said, we're going to resign from the Corps.
He said, well, take your buttons off and I'll take them.
Boy, they all looked at him, you know, and a couple walked up and he said, you're going to lose your contract, too.
And boy, that broke the thing up right quick.
I don't know what they were marching for, but they had some of them.
He was very strong, and I think that's why they picked him to go to Korea.
They made him a brigadier after he got there.
So you were, in today's slang, you were a TAC officer.
In today's slang, yeah.
For how long?
Well, from 51 to, when did I go to work?
I went to work out at the National Guard Armory, I guess.
I was there about four years.
Four years.
Were there any?
Three and a half years.
Who were the key campus administrators during that four years?
Well, Benny Zinn was one of them, and Dean Brooks was the dean of the college.
Joe David.
Who?
Joe Davis.
He was assistant commandant and then actually became commandant for a while.
That was after I left, I think.
Who was president?
Well, we had two presidents.
One of them's name was Wayne, I think.
That's not right.
That's not right.
Because Morgan wasn't here yet, was he?
Morgan came in, I think, just before.
He replaced another guy that replaced Gib Gilchrist.
Okay, okay.
I think Morgan was here.
Yeah, I think Morgan was here, but there was somebody in between he and Gib Gilchrist.
All right, so then you go to the armory, and then you come back to A&M when?
I came back to A&M in 1963.
What was your task then?
I was a civilian counselor.
Oh, I know a question I meant to ask.
What was your compensation?
What was your pay that first job when you came, what, in 51?
Do you remember what that pay was?
I don't remember in 51.
I was teaching school.
I started out at $200 a month.
By the time I left over there, I was getting $240.
That was before taxes.
So you got a big, when you came over here at $400.
That's the reason I came, yeah.
All right, now you come back in 63.
And what's your task?
I'm called a civilian counselor because we had a lot of civilians.
You were a counselor.
Yeah, civilian student counselor, because they had a lot of civilian students then.
And what were, describe the duties of a civilian counselor.
Well, they were similar to what they were as a TAC officer.
We kept, we, you're dang right I checked them.
I didn't have to, but their rooms were supposed to be clean.
And all of us inspected the room.
We didn't look in every room every day.
And we supervised and hired the dorm daddies.
And we kept personnel files on all of the kids in our dormitories.
Now, when I first came back, I had Walton Hall and some of the new area, new, new area.
And I kept, I kept,
Records on that.
So you're on board when the Corps becomes volunteer.
Yes.
How did that change?
I'm sorry.
It had already become volunteer when I got here.
But the big growth in the number, I presume the civilian student body grew rapidly.
Well, pretty rapidly.
The core began to diminish a little bit because the kids that finished there were coming in.
When it first became validated, the first two years were mandatory, then you could be a civilian.
And I'm not sure of the dates on that.
Yeah, the civilian population was pretty good.
And civilian students were living where?
Well, they lived in Hart Hall, they lived in Leggett, they lived in Mitchell.
They lived in Milner, they lived in Walton Hall, and one of the dorms in the Nunu area, and the Corps had the rest of the place.
And you civilian counselors reported to whom?
Benny Zinn.
Describe Mr. Zinn.
Wonderful guy.
He was even-tempered, he was white-headed, he was so friendly.
To us.
And I think Doris knows him as well as I do because when she worked out there, he was one of her bosses.
But she couldn't work after I went to A&M.
She had to give her job up.
And he was a wonderful guy.
And he took Penny...
He was dean of students at one time and they mistreated, they held Penny responsible for a lot of things they did and so they did away with the dean of students for a little while.
